3.1.1 Simulation Study

Method

  1. Simulate \(n = 5000\) complete values of the binary 0/1 covariate \(x\) and binary 0/1 outcome \(y\) from the following models.

\[x \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p_x^{pop} = 0.7);\] \[\text{logit}[p(y = 1 | x)] = \beta_0 + \beta_x x,\]

where \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_x\) are arbitrarily set to \(ln(0.5)\) and \(ln(1.5)\), respectively. The same values of the \(\beta\) parameters are used throughout to make bias comparable across all simulation settings. This sample size is chosen to minimize the issue of small-sample bias associated with logistic regression.

library(knitr)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
library(vcd)
library(locfit) #used for expit function
library(mice)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(xtable)
n = 5000
pop_x = 0.7

#simulate the x values
X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)

#simulate the y values
beta_0 = log(0.5)
beta_x = log(1.5)
Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))

#combine resutls into a data frame
completeData = data.frame(X, Y)

#convert X and Y columns to factors
completeData$X = as.factor(completeData$X)
completeData$Y = as.factor(completeData$Y)

#see if the sample of x values is distributed approximately as expected
ggplot(data = completeData, aes(x = X)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = X)) + 
  geom_text(
    aes(label = after_stat(prop*100), group = 1, vjust = -0.25),
    stat = 'count'
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

table(completeData)
##    Y
## X      0    1
##   0 1014  521
##   1 1999 1466
data_table = structable(Y ~ X)
mosaic(data_table, shade = TRUE, legend = FALSE)

This table summarizes the joint probability of \(x\) and \(y\):

\(y = 0\) \(y = 1\)
\(x = 0\) \(0.3(1 - \text{expit}(ln(0.5) + ln(1.5)*0)) = 0.2\) \(0.3(\text{expit}(ln(0.5) + ln(1.5)*0)) = 0.1\) \(p(x = 0) = 0.3\)
\(x = 1\) \(0.7(1 - \text{expit}(ln(0.5) + ln(1.5)*1)) = 0.4\) \(0.7(\text{expit}(ln(0.5) + ln(1.5)*1)) = 0.3\) \(p(x = 1) = 0.7\)
\(p(y = 0) = 0.6\) \(p(y = 1) = 0.4\)

Missingness Mechanisms

  1. Simulate a binary indicator of response \(r\) of \(x\) from each of the selection models M1 to M4 (Table 1C). Values of 1.5 and -1.5 are chosen for \(\alpha_y\) and \(\alpha_x\) in M2 and M3, respectively, to reflect strong odds ratios (\(OR\)s) of observing \(x\) (\(OR = 4.5\) and \(0.2\), respectively). For M4, \(\alpha_y = 1.5\) and \(\alpha_x = -1.5\) are chosen as bias in the two MI methods under evaluation is likely to be apparent with these coefficients predicting missingness in \(x\). For all selection models, \(\alpha_0\) is altered to achieve approximately 45% missing \(x\). For M1, \(\alpha_0\) is calculated directly as \(ln(\frac{0.55}{0.45})\); for M2 to M4, \(\alpha_0 = -0.2; 1.35\) and \(0.75\) appear to work well.

That is, \(\text{logit}[p(r = 1 | x, y)] = \alpha_0 + \alpha_y y + \alpha_x x\), with the following parameter values used for this simulation study:

Missingness Mechanism/Parameter Value \(\alpha_0\) \(\alpha_y\) \(\alpha_x\)
M1 ln(0.55/0.45) 0 0
M2 -0.2 1.5 0
M3 1.35 0 -1.5
M4 0.75 1.5 -1.5

Note that:

  • In M1, missingness in \(x\) occurs randomly; the value of \(x\) and \(y\) do not affect the probability that x is missing. That is, M1 simulates data missing completely at random (MCAR).
    Under M1, \(r \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p = 0.55)\), and therefore \(E[r] = 0.55\) and \(Var[p] = 0.55*0.45 = 0.2475\). We can use the Central Limit Theorem to approximate a 95% confidence interval for \(\bar r\), which is the proportion of missing \(x\) values in the sample of 5000. That is, \(0.55 \pm 1.96 \sqrt{0.2475/5000} = (0.536, 0.564)\) is a 95% CI for \(\bar r\).
  • In M2, missingness in \(x\) is related to the value of \(y\). Specifically, if \(y\) is 0, the probability that \(x\) is observed is \(\text{expit} (-0.2 + 1.5*0) \approx 0.450\). If \(y\) is 1, the probability that \(x\) is observed is \(\text{expit} (-0.2 + 1.5*1) \approx 0.786\). In this mechanism, \(x\) is missing at random (MAR) conditional on \(y\). I.e., if we know the value of \(y\), missingness in \(x\) occurs at random. Under M2, \(r|y \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p = \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5 y))\).
    \[ \begin{aligned} E[r|y] &= \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y) \\ \end{aligned} \] By the law of iterated expectations:
    \[ \begin{aligned} E[r] &= E[E[r|y]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)] \\ &= \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5*0)*p(y = 0) + \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5*1)*p(y = 1) \\ &= \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5*0)*0.6 + \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5*1)*0.4 \\ &\approx 0.584 \end{aligned} \]
expit(-0.2 + 1.5*0)*0.6 + expit(-0.2 + 1.5*1)*0.4
## [1] 0.5844336

By the conditional variance identity:
\[ \begin{aligned} Var[r] &= E[Var[r|y]] + Var[E[r|y]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)(1 - \text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y))] + Var[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)] - E[(\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y))^2] + E[(\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y))^2] - (E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)])^2 \\ &= E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)] - (E[\text{expit}(-0.2 + 1.5y)])^2 \\ &\approx 0.584 - 0.584^2 \\ &\approx 0.243 \end{aligned} \]

Again can use the Central Limit Theorem to approximate a 95% confidence interval for \(\bar r\), which is the proportion of missing \(x\) values in the sample of 5000. That is, \(0.584 \pm 1.96 \sqrt{0.243/5000} = (0.570, 0.598)\) is a 95% CI for \(\bar r\).
That is, for every 100 data sets of size 5000 generated randomly under M2, we would expect that 95 of them would contain between 57.0% and 59.8% observed \(x\). We can check this with a simulation:

#find CI for r under the M2 mechanism via simulation.

S = 5000
pctObserved = matrix(nrow = S, ncol = 1)

for (i in 1:S) {
  n = 5000
  pop_x = 0.7
  
  #simulate the x values
  X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)
  
  #simulate the y values
  beta_0 = log(0.5)
  beta_x = log(1.5)
  Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))
  

  #simulation r values
  alpha_0 = -0.2
  alpha_y = 1.5
  M2 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_y * Y))
  
  #calculate percentage of observed values under M2
  pctObserved[i, 1] = mean(M2)
  
}

plot(density(pctObserved))

mean(pctObserved)
## [1] 0.5844254
quantile(pctObserved, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 0.570795 0.598400

Question: Is there a better choice for \(\alpha_0\) in the M2 scenario? The stated objective is to obtain about 55% observed \(x\), but we see that 0.55 is outside of the 95% confidence interval for \(\hat r\). We can solve for \(\alpha_0\) numerically:

\[ \begin{aligned} E[r] &= E[E[r|y]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5y)] \\ &= \text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5*0)*p(y = 0) + \text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5*1)*p(y = 1) \\ &= \text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5*0)*0.6 + \text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5*1)*0.4 \\ &= \text{expit}(\alpha_0)*0.6 + \text{expit}(\alpha_0 + 1.5)*0.4 \\ &\overset{set}{=}0.55 \end{aligned} \]

fn = function(alpha_0) {
  abs(expit(alpha_0) * 0.6 + expit(alpha_0 + 1.5) * 0.4 - 0.55)
}
optimize(fn, interval = c(-3, 3), maximum = FALSE)
## $minimum
## [1] -0.3583884
## 
## $objective
## [1] 1.363527e-08

Lets run the simulation study again, using the more precise value of \(\alpha_0\):

#find CI for r under the M2 mechanism via simulation, using more accurate alpha_0

S = 5000
pctObserved = matrix(nrow = S, ncol = 1)

for (i in 1:S) {
  n = 5000
  pop_x = 0.7
  
  #simulate the x values
  X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)
  
  #simulate the y values
  beta_0 = log(0.5)
  beta_x = log(1.5)
  Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))
  

  #simulation r values
  alpha_0 = -0.3583884
  alpha_y = 1.5
  M2 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_y * Y))
  
  #calculate percentage of observed values under M2
  pctObserved[i, 1] = mean(M2)
  
}

plot(density(pctObserved))

mean(pctObserved)
## [1] 0.5501391
quantile(pctObserved, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 0.536795 0.564000
  • In M3, missingness in \(x\) is related to the value of \(x\) itself. Specifically, if \(x\) is 0, the probability that \(x\) is observed is \(\text{expit} (1.35 - 1.5*0) \approx 0.794\). If \(y\) is 1, the probability that \(x\) is observed is \(\text{expit} (1.35 - 1.5*1) \approx 0.463\). In this mechanism, the probability of observing \(x\) depends on the value of \(x\) itself, so \(x\) is missing not at random (MNAR). Under M3, \(r|x \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p = \text{expit}(-0.2 - 1.5 x))\).
    \[ \begin{aligned} E[r|x] &= \text{expit}(-0.2 - 1.5x) \\ \end{aligned} \] By the law of iterated expectations:
    \[ \begin{aligned} E[r] &= E[E[r|x]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)] \\ &= \text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5*0)*p(x = 0) + \text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5*1)*p(x = 1) \\ &= \text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5*0)*0.3 + \text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5*1)*0.7 \\ &\approx 0.562 \end{aligned} \]
expit(1.35 - 1.5*0)*0.3 + expit(1.35 - 1.5*1)*0.7
## [1] 0.562038

By the conditional variance identity:
\[ \begin{aligned} Var[r] &= E[Var[r|x]] + Var[E[r|x]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)(1 - \text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x))] + Var[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)] - E[(\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x))^2] + E[(\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x))^2] - (E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)])^2 \\ &= E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)] - (E[\text{expit}(1.35 - 1.5x)])^2 \\ &\approx 0.562 - 0.562^2 \\ &\approx 0.246 \end{aligned} \]

Again can use the Central Limit Theorem to approximate a 95% confidence interval for \(\bar r\), which is the proportion of missing \(x\) values in the sample of 5000. That is, \(0.562 \pm 1.96 \sqrt{0.246/5000} = (0.548, 0.576)\) is a 95% CI for \(\bar r\).
That is, for every 100 data sets of size 5000 generated randomly under M3, we would expect that 95 of them would contain between 54.8% and 57.6% observed \(x\). We can check this with a simulation:

#find CI for r under the M3 mechanism via simulation.

S = 5000
pctObserved = matrix(nrow = S, ncol = 1)

for (i in 1:S) {
  n = 5000
  pop_x = 0.7
  
  #simulate the x values
  X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)
  
  #simulate the y values
  beta_0 = log(0.5)
  beta_x = log(1.5)
  Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))
  
  
  #simulation r values
  alpha_0 = 1.35
  alpha_x = -1.5
  M3 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x * X))
  
  #calculate percentage of observed values under M2
  pctObserved[i, 1] = mean(M3)
  
}

plot(density(pctObserved))

mean(pctObserved)
## [1] 0.5621177
quantile(pctObserved, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 0.548200 0.575805
  • In M4, missingness in \(x\) is related to the value of \(y\) and the value of \(x\). This is another MNAR mechanism. The table below summarizes the probabilities of observing \(x\) conditioned on the values of \(x\) and \(y\):
Actual x/Actual y 0 1
0 \(p(r = 1 | x = 0, y = 0) = \text{expit}(0.75) \approx 0.679\) \(p(r = 1 | x = 0, y = 1) = \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5) \approx 0.905\)
1 \(p(r = 1 | x = 1, y = 0) = \text{expit}(0.75-1.5) \approx 0.321\) \(p(r = 1 | x = 1, y = 1) = \text{expit}(0.75) \approx 0.679\)

Under M4, \(r|x,y \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p = \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x))\).
\[ \begin{aligned} E[r|x] &= \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x) \\ \end{aligned} \] By the law of iterated expectations:
\[ \begin{aligned} E[r] &= E[E[r|x,y]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)] \\ &= \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5*0 - 1.5*0)*p(x = 0, y = 0) + \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5*0 - 1.5*1)*p(x = 1, y = 0) \\ & \quad+ \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5*1 - 1.5*0)*p(x = 0, y = 1) + \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5*1 - 1.5*1)*p(x = 1, y = 1)\\ &\approx 0.679*0.2 + 0.321*0.4 + 0.905*0.1 + 0.679*0.3\\ &\approx 0.558 \end{aligned} \]

0.679 * 0.2 + 0.321 * 0.4 + 0.905 * 0.1 + 0.679 * 0.3
## [1] 0.5584

By the conditional variance identity:
\[ \begin{aligned} Var[r] &= E[Var[r|x, y]] + Var[E[r|x,y]] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)(1 - \text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x))] + Var[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)] \\ &= E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)] - E[(\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x))^2] + E[(\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x))^2] - (E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)])^2 \\ &= E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)] - (E[\text{expit}(0.75 + 1.5y - 1.5x)])^2 \\ &\approx 0.558 - 0.558^2 \\ &\approx 0.247 \end{aligned} \]

Again can use the Central Limit Theorem to approximate a 95% confidence interval for \(\bar r\), which is the proportion of missing \(x\) values in the sample of 5000. That is, \(0.558 \pm 1.96 \sqrt{0.247/5000} = (0.544, 0.572)\) is a 95% CI for \(\bar r\).
That is, for every 100 data sets of size 5000 generated randomly under M4, we would expect that 95 of them would contain between 54.4% and 57.2% observed \(x\). We can check this with a simulation:

#find CI for r under the M4 mechanism via simulation.

S = 5000
pctObserved = matrix(nrow = S, ncol = 1)

for (i in 1:S) {
  n = 5000
  pop_x = 0.7
  
  #simulate the x values
  X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)
  
  #simulate the y values
  beta_0 = log(0.5)
  beta_x = log(1.5)
  Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))
  
  
  #simulation r values
  alpha_0 = 0.75
  alpha_y = 1.5
  alpha_x = -1.5
  M4 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x*X + alpha_y*Y))
  
  #calculate percentage of observed values under M2
  pctObserved[i, 1] = mean(M4)
  
}

plot(density(pctObserved))

mean(pctObserved)
## [1] 0.5583506
quantile(pctObserved, c(0.025, 0.975))
##   2.5%  97.5% 
## 0.5446 0.5722

M1: \(\text{logit}[p(r = 1 | x, y)] = \alpha_0\)

alpha_0 = log(0.55/0.45)
M1 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0))

M2: \(\text{logit}[p(r = 1 | x, y)] = \alpha_0 + \alpha_y y\)

alpha_0 = -0.2
alpha_y = 1.5
M2 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_y * Y))

M3: \(\text{logit}[p(r = 1 | x, y)] = \alpha_0 + \alpha_x x\)

alpha_0 = 1.35
alpha_x = -1.5
M3 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x * X))

M4: \(\text{logit}[p(r = 1 | x, y)] = \alpha_0 + \alpha_x x + \alpha_y y\)

alpha_0 = 0.75
alpha_y = 1.5
alpha_x = -1.5
M4 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x * X + alpha_y * Y))
  1. For \(i = 1,...,5000\), set \(x_i\) to missing if \(r_i = 0\).

Imputation using calibrated-\(\delta\)

  1. Impute missing values in \(x\) \(M=50\) times using standard MI and calibrated-\(\delta\) adjustment MI in turn.
    First well start with standard MI on the M1 data set:
M1_MI = mice(data = M1_data, m = 50, print = FALSE)

Now lets try calibrated-\(\delta\) adjustment MI:

  1. Fit a logistic regression imputation model for \(x\) conditional on \(y\) to the complete records to obtain the maximum likelihood estimates of the imputation models parameters \(\hat \theta\) and their asymptotic sampling variance \(\hat U\).
M1_log_reg = glm(X ~ Y,
                 data = M1_data,
                 family = "binomial",
                 na.action = na.exclude)

M1_summary = summary(M1_log_reg)

theta_hat = M1_summary$coefficients[, 1]
U_hat = M1_summary$coefficients[, 2] ^ 2
  1. Draw new parameters \(\tilde \theta\) from the large-sample normal approximation \(N \left(\hat \theta, \hat U \right)\) of their posterior distribution, assuming non-informative priors.
theta_0_tilde = rnorm(n = 1, mean = theta_hat[1], sd = sqrt(U_hat[1]))
theta_y_tilde = rnorm(n = 1, mean = theta_hat[2], sd = sqrt(U_hat[2]))
  1. Draw a new probability of observing \(x\), \(\tilde p_r\), from the normal approximation \(N \left(\hat p_r, \frac{\hat p_r (1 - \hat p_r)}{n} \right)\), where \(\hat p_r\) is the sample proportion of the response indicator of \(x\), \(\hat p_r = \frac{n_{++}^{obs}}{n_{++}}\).
    [Note that the \(++\) subscript is used in the same way the \(..\) subscript is used in the regression setting.]
n = 5000
p_r_hat = mean(M1)
p_r_tilde = rnorm(n = 1, mean = p_r_hat, sd = sqrt(p_r_hat*(1 - p_r_hat)/n))
  1. Draw a new probability of observed \(x = 1\), \(\tilde p_x\), from the normal approximation \(N \left(\hat p_x, \frac{\hat p_x (1 - \hat p_x)}{n} \right)\), where \(\hat p_x\) is the observed proportion of \(x = 1\), \(\hat p_x = \frac{n_{1+}^{obs}}{n_{++}^{obs}}\).
#can use this expression to calculate p_x_hat:
#length(M1_data$X[which(M1_data$X == 1)])/length(M1_data$X[which(!is.na(M1_data$X))])

#but this way is shorter. We need the minus 1 because when R converts to numeric,
#the (0, 1) become (1, 2).
p_x_hat = mean(as.numeric(M1_data$X) - 1, na.rm = TRUE)
p_x_tilde = rnorm(n = 1, mean = p_x_hat, sd = sqrt(p_x_hat * (1 - p_x_hat)/n))
  1. Derive the value of the calibrated \(\delta\)-adjustment from the equation

\[\frac{1}{n^{miss}} \sum_{i = 1}^{n^{mis}} \text{expit}[(\tilde \theta_0 + \delta) + \tilde \theta_y y_i] = \frac{p_x^{pop} - \tilde p_x \tilde p_r}{1 - \tilde p_r}\]

where \(p_x^{pop}\) is the probability of \(x = 1\) in the population.

p_x_pop = 0.7

delta_equation = function(delta) {
  #extract only the rows of the data where x is missing
  missing_x = M1_data[which(is.na(M1_data$X)),]
  
  #calculate left hand side of the equation
  LHS = mean(expit((theta_0_tilde + delta) + theta_y_tilde * (as.numeric(missing_x$Y) - 1)))
  
  #calculate right hand side of the equation
  RHS = (p_x_pop - p_x_tilde * p_r_tilde) / (1 - p_r_tilde)

  #return function to minimize
  (LHS - RHS)^2
}

delta = optimize(delta_equation,
                 lower = -10,
                 upper = 10,
                 maximum = FALSE)$minimum
  1. Fit the logistic regression imputation model for \(x\) conditional on \(y\) (in step 1) to the complete records with the intercept adjustment fixed to \(\delta\) to obtain the maximum likelihood estimates of the imputation models parameters \(\hat \theta\) and their asymptotic sampling variance \(\hat U\).

Due to the invariance property of the MLE, we dont need to refit a logistic regression model. The asymptotic posterior distribution is simply \(N(\tilde \theta_0 + \delta, \tilde U_0)\).

  1. Draw new parameters \(\mathbf{\theta}\) from the large-sample normal approximation \(N \left(\hat \theta, \hat U \right)\), assuming non-informative priors.
theta_0 = rnorm(n = 1,
                      mean = theta_hat[1] + delta,
                      sd = sqrt(U_hat[1]))

theta_y = rnorm(n = 1,
                      mean = theta_hat[2],
                      sd = sqrt(U_hat[2]))
  1. Draw imputed values for \(x\) from the aforementioned logistic regression imputation model (specifically, \(\text{logit}[p(x = 1|y)]=\theta_0 + \theta_y y\)), using the newly drawn parameters \(\mathbf{\theta}\) and calibrated-\(\delta\) adjustment.
M1_data  = M1_data %>%
  mutate(Probs = expit(theta_0 + theta_y * as.numeric(Y))) %>%
  mutate(Preds = rbinom(
    n = nrow(M1_data),
    size = 1,
    prob = Probs
  )) %>%
  mutate(X_complete = ifelse(is.na(X), Preds, as.numeric(X) - 1)) 

#have to subtract 1 when converting from factor to number; otherwise R uses 1 and 2.

Now we have to turn all this into a loop:

#This function returns 1 completed set of X values
#incomplete_data argument must contain X and Y columns; p_pop is a known constant

CalibratedDelta = function(incomplete_data, p_x_pop) {
  #fit the logistic regression model on the complete data
  rx = !is.na(incomplete_data$X)
  design.mat = cbind(1, as.numeric(incomplete_data$Y) - 1)
  X = as.numeric(incomplete_data$X) - 1
  
  fit = glm.fit(x = design.mat[rx, ], y = X[rx],
                    family = binomial(link = logit))
  fit.sum = summary.glm(fit)
  
  #extract MLE of mean and variances for model params
  theta_hat = coef(fit)
  #U_hat = summary_log_reg$coefficients[, 2] ^ 2
  rv = t(chol(fit.sum$cov.unscaled))
  
  #draw new theta tilde params from the asymptotic distribution
  theta_tilde = theta_hat + rv %*% rnorm(ncol(rv))
  
  #draw new probability of observing x from the normal approximation
  n = nrow(incomplete_data)
  p_r_hat = mean(rx)
  p_r_tilde = rnorm(n = 1,
                    mean = p_r_hat,
                    sd = sqrt(p_r_hat * (1 - p_r_hat) / n))
  
  #draw new probability of observing x = 1 from the normal approximation
  p_x_hat = mean(as.numeric(incomplete_data$X[rx])) - 1
  p_x_tilde = rnorm(n = 1,
                    mean = p_x_hat,
                    sd = sqrt(p_x_hat * (1 - p_x_hat) / n))
  
  #derive the calibrated delta adjustment
  delta_equation = function(delta) {
    #extract only the rows of the data where x is missing
    missing_x = incomplete_data[which(is.na(incomplete_data$X)), ]
    
    #calculate left hand side of the equation
    LHS = mean(expit((theta_tilde[1] + delta) + theta_tilde[2] * (as.numeric(missing_x$Y) - 1)))
    
    #calculate right hand side of the equation
    RHS = (p_x_pop - p_x_tilde * p_r_tilde) / (1 - p_r_tilde)
    
    #return function to minimize
    (LHS - RHS)^2
  }
  
  delta = optimize(
    delta_equation,
    lower = -10,
    upper = 10,
    maximum = FALSE
  )$minimum

  theta_tilde[1] = theta_tilde[1] + delta
  
  theta = theta_tilde + rv %*% rnorm(ncol(rv))

  #try binomial draw instead
  p = expit(design.mat[!rx, ] %*% theta)
  vec = (runif(nrow(p)) <= p)
  vec[vec] = 1
  if (is.factor(incomplete_data$X)) {
    vec = factor(vec, c(0, 1), levels(incomplete_data$X))
  }
  
  incomplete_data$X_complete = incomplete_data$X
  incomplete_data$X_complete[!rx] = vec
  
  
  #fit logistic regression model to complete data
  log_reg_final = glm(
    Y ~ X_complete,
    data = incomplete_data,
    family = "binomial"
  )
  
  beta = summary(log_reg_final)$coefficients[, 1:2]
  return(beta)
}
Rubin = function(M, incomplete_data, p_x_pop){
  results = t(replicate(M, 
                        as.vector(CalibratedDelta(incomplete_data, p_x_pop)), 
                        simplify = "array"))
  Q = apply(results[,1:2], 2, mean)
  U = apply(results[,3:4]^2, 2, mean)  #mean variances from imputation
  B = apply(results[,1:2], 2, var)     #between imputation variances
  Tm = U + (1 + M^-1)*B      #combined variances
  return(list(Est = Q, SE = sqrt(Tm)))
}

Standard Multiple Imputation with MICE

#impute data using traditional MI, using MICE
MI.Results = function(M, incomplete_data) {
  results = mice(data = incomplete_data, 
                 m = M, 
                 method = "logreg", 
                 printFlag = FALSE)
  fit = with(data = results, exp = glm(Y ~ X, family = "binomial"))
  tbl = summary(pool(fit))
  return(list(Est = tbl$estimate, SE = tbl$std.error))
}

Outline

Simulate a missingness mechanism 2000 times

Each time:
* Fit using MICE
* Fit using calibrated-delta adjustment
* Fit using CRA
* Return estimates, standard errors, and the coverage of 95% confidence intervals

#generates a 5000x2 data frame of X and Y observations, 
#based on the specifications in the paper.

CreateData = function() {
  n = 5000
  pop_x = 0.7
  
  #simulate the x values
  X = rbinom(n, size = 1, pop_x)
  
  #simulate the y values
  beta_0 = log(0.5)
  beta_x = log(1.5)
  Y = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(beta_0 + beta_x * X))
  
  #combine resutls into a data frame
  completeData = data.frame(X, Y)
  
  #convert X and Y columns to factors
  completeData$X = as.factor(completeData$X)
  completeData$Y = as.factor(completeData$Y)
  
  return(completeData)
}
M1.Missingness.Mechanism = function(data) {
  n = nrow(data)
  alpha_0 = log(0.55 / 0.45)
  M1 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0))
  data$X[which(M1 == 0)] = NA
  return(data)
}

M2.Missingness.Mechanism = function(data) {
  n = nrow(data)
  alpha_0 = -0.2
  alpha_y = 1.5
  Y = as.numeric(data$Y) - 1
  M2 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_y * Y))
  data$X[which(M2 == 0)] = NA
  return(data)
}

M3.Missingness.Mechanism = function(data) {
  n = nrow(data)
  alpha_0 = 1.35
  alpha_x = -1.5
  X = as.numeric(data$X) - 1
  M3 = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x * X))
  data$X[which(M3 == 0)] = NA
  return(data)
}

M4.Missingness.Mechanism = function(data) {
  n = nrow(data)
  alpha_0 = 0.75
  alpha_y = 1.5
  alpha_x = -1.5
  X = as.numeric(data$X) - 1
  Y = as.numeric(data$Y) - 1
  M4 = rbinom(n,
              size = 1,
              prob = expit(alpha_0 + alpha_x * X + alpha_y * Y))
  data$X[which(M4 == 0)] = NA
  return(data)
}
Rubin_EstPopProp = function(M, incomplete_data, p_x_pop, n_ex) {
  results = t(replicate(M, 
                        as.vector(CalibratedDelta_EstPopProp(incomplete_data, p_x_pop, n_ex)), 
                        simplify = "array"))
  Q = apply(results[,1:2], 2, mean)
  U = apply(results[,3:4]^2, 2, mean)  #mean variances from imputation
  B = apply(results[,1:2], 2, var)     #between imputation variances
  Tm = U + (1 + M^-1)*B      #combined variances
  return(list(Est = Q, SE = sqrt(Tm)))
}
CalibratedDelta_EstPopProp = function(incomplete_data, p_x_pop_est, n_ex) {
  #fit the logistic regression model on the complete data
  rx = !is.na(incomplete_data$X)
  design.mat = cbind(1, as.numeric(incomplete_data$Y) - 1)
  X = as.numeric(incomplete_data$X) - 1
  
  fit = glm.fit(x = design.mat[rx, ], y = X[rx],
                    family = binomial(link = logit))
  fit.sum = summary.glm(fit)
  
  #extract MLE of mean and variances for model params
  theta_hat = coef(fit)
  #U_hat = summary_log_reg$coefficients[, 2] ^ 2
  rv = t(chol(fit.sum$cov.unscaled))
  
  #draw new theta tilde params from the asymptotic distribution
  theta_tilde = theta_hat + rv %*% rnorm(ncol(rv))
  
  #draw new probability of observing x from the normal approximation
  n = nrow(incomplete_data)
  p_r_hat = mean(rx)
  p_r_tilde = rnorm(n = 1,
                    mean = p_r_hat,
                    sd = sqrt(p_r_hat * (1 - p_r_hat) / n))
  
  #draw new probability of observing x = 1 from the normal approximation
  p_x_hat = mean(as.numeric(incomplete_data$X[rx])) - 1
  p_x_tilde = rnorm(n = 1,
                    mean = p_x_hat,
                    sd = sqrt(p_x_hat * (1 - p_x_hat) / n))
  
  #draw a p_x_pop from the asymptotic distribution
  p_x_pop = rnorm(n = 1, 
                  mean = p_x_pop_est, 
                  sd = sqrt(p_x_pop_est * (1 - p_x_pop_est)/n_ex))

  #derive the calibrated delta adjustment
  delta_equation = function(delta) {
    #extract only the rows of the data where x is missing
    missing_x = incomplete_data[which(is.na(incomplete_data$X)), ]
    
    #calculate left hand side of the equation
    LHS = mean(expit((theta_tilde[1] + delta) + theta_tilde[2] * (as.numeric(missing_x$Y) - 1)))
    
    #calculate right hand side of the equation
    RHS = (p_x_pop - p_x_tilde * p_r_tilde) / (1 - p_r_tilde)
    
    #return function to minimize
    (LHS - RHS)^2
  }
  
  delta = optimize(
    delta_equation,
    lower = -10,
    upper = 10,
    maximum = FALSE
  )$minimum
  # 
  #delta = optim(par = 0, fn = delta_equation, lower = -10, upper = 10, method = "Brent")$par
  #print(delta)
  #draw theta parameters, incorporating the delta adjustment
  # theta = mvrnorm(n = 1, 
  #                 mu = c(theta_0_tilde + delta, theta_y_tilde),
  #                 Sigma = t(chol(V)))
  
  theta_tilde[1] = theta_tilde[1] + delta
  
  theta = theta_tilde + rv %*% rnorm(ncol(rv))

  #try binomial draw instead
  p = expit(design.mat[!rx, ] %*% theta)
  vec = (runif(nrow(p)) <= p)
  vec[vec] = 1
  if (is.factor(incomplete_data$X)) {
    vec = factor(vec, c(0, 1), levels(incomplete_data$X))
  }
  
  incomplete_data$X_complete = incomplete_data$X
  incomplete_data$X_complete[!rx] = vec
  
  
  #fit logistic regression model to complete data
  log_reg_final = glm(
    Y ~ X_complete,
    data = incomplete_data,
    family = "binomial"
  )
  
  beta = summary(log_reg_final)$coefficients[, 1:2]
  return(beta)
}
#missingness.mechanism can take on "M1", "M2", "M3", or "M4"
sims = function(S, M, pop_x, missingness.mechanism) {
  sims_res = data.frame(
    Iter = integer(),
    Method = character(),
    est_beta_0 = double(),
    est_beta_1 = double(),
    SE_beta_0 = double(),
    SE_beta_1 = double(),
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
  )
  
  print(paste("Starting", S, missingness.mechanism, "simulations at", Sys.time()))
  tictoc::tic()
  for (i in 1:S) {
    
    complete_data = CreateData()
    incomplete_data = switch(missingness.mechanism, 
           "M1" = M1.Missingness.Mechanism(complete_data),
           "M2" = M2.Missingness.Mechanism(complete_data), 
           "M3" = M3.Missingness.Mechanism(complete_data),
           "M4" = M4.Missingness.Mechanism(complete_data))

    #create data frame to hold results of this iteration
    iter_res = data.frame(
      Iter = integer(),
      Method = character(),
      est_beta_0 = double(),
      est_beta_1 = double(),
      SE_beta_0 = double(),
      SE_beta_1 = double(),
      stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    )
    #full data
    log_reg_full = glm(Y ~ X,
                       data = complete_data,
                       family = "binomial")
    Full_Est = log_reg_full$coefficients
    Full_SE = coef(summary(log_reg_full))[, "Std. Error"]
    iter_res[1,] = c(i, "Full data", Full_Est, Full_SE)

    #CRA on incomplete data
    log_reg_CRA = glm(Y ~ X,
                      data = incomplete_data,
                      family = "binomial",
                      na.action = na.exclude)
    CRA_Est = log_reg_CRA$coefficients
    CRA_SE = coef(summary(log_reg_CRA))[, "Std. Error"]
    iter_res = rbind(iter_res, c(i, "CCA", CRA_Est, CRA_SE))

    #Standard MI (with MICE)
    MI_Res = MI.Results(M, incomplete_data)
    iter_res = rbind(iter_res, c(i, "Standard MI", unlist(MI_Res)))

    #Calibrated Delta method
    CalibratedDeltaRes = Rubin(M, incomplete_data, pop_x)
    iter_res = rbind(iter_res, c(i, "Calibrated Delta", unlist(CalibratedDeltaRes)))

    #Calibrated Delta with estimated population parameter, pop size = 10,000
    #get p_hat_x_pop for given population size
    p_hat_x_prop = mean(rbinom(n = 10000, size = 1, prob = pop_x))
    CalibratedDeltaRes_EstPopProp = Rubin_EstPopProp(M, incomplete_data, 
                                                     p_hat_x_prop, 10000)
    iter_res = rbind(iter_res, c(i, "Calibrated Delta 10000",
                                 unlist(CalibratedDeltaRes_EstPopProp)))
    
    #Calibrated Delta with estimated population parameter, pop size = 1000
    #get p_hat_x_pop for given population size
    p_hat_x_prop = mean(rbinom(n = 1000, size = 1, prob = pop_x))
    CalibratedDeltaRes_EstPopProp = Rubin_EstPopProp(M, incomplete_data, 
                                                     p_hat_x_prop, 1000)
    iter_res = rbind(iter_res, c(i, "Calibrated Delta 1000",
                                 unlist(CalibratedDeltaRes_EstPopProp)))
    iter_res = iter_res %>% 
      mutate_at(c("est_beta_0", "est_beta_1", "SE_beta_0", "SE_beta_1"), as.numeric)
    sims_res = rbind(sims_res, iter_res)
    #i = 2
    if ((i %% 200) == 0) {
      print(paste(i, "of", S, "simulations complete at", Sys.time()))
    }
  }
  tictoc::toc()
  return(sims_res)
}


M1Sims = sims(2000, 50, 0.7, "M1")
write.csv(M1Sims, "M1_results.csv")

M2Sims = sims(2000, 50, 0.7, "M2")

  xlab(expression(paste("Bias of ", beta[0]))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-0.02, 0.02)) +
  labs(title = expression(paste("Average Bias of ", beta[0]))) +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = labs) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(19, 4), guide = "none") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom", 
        legend.direction="vertical", 
        legend.text.align = 0,
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        strip.background =element_rect(fill="white")) +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  facet_wrap(~MissingnessMechanism, ncol = 1) 

beta_x_bias = summary %>% 
   mutate(OutOfBounds = abs(avg_bias_beta_x) > 0.02,
         avg_bias_beta_x = if_else(OutOfBounds, 0.02 * sign(avg_bias_beta_x), avg_bias_beta_x)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = Method, x = avg_bias_beta_x, color = Method, shape = OutOfBounds)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  xlab(expression(paste("Bias of ", beta[x]))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-0.02, 0.02)) +
  labs(title = expression(paste("Average Bias of ", beta[x]))) +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = labs) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(19, 4), guide = "none") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom", 
        legend.direction="vertical", 
        legend.text.align = 0,
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        strip.background =element_rect(fill="white")) +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  facet_wrap(~MissingnessMechanism, ncol = 1) 

# arrange the three plots in a single row
prow <- plot_grid(beta_0_bias + theme(legend.position="none"),
           beta_x_bias + theme(legend.position="none"),
           align = 'vh',
           #labels = c("A", "B", "C"),
           hjust = -1,
           nrow = 1
           )


# extract the legend from one of the plots
# (clearly the whole thing only makes sense if all plots
# have the same legend, so we can arbitrarily pick one.)
legend_b <- get_legend(beta_0_bias + theme(legend.position="bottom"))

# add the legend underneath the row we made earlier. Give it 10% of the height
# of one plot (via rel_heights).
p <- plot_grid( prow, legend_b, ncol = 1, rel_heights = c(1, .2))
p

Get 95% CI coverage probabilities:

#Get 95% empirical CI for each iteration

CIs = left_join(AllSims, summary, by = c("MissingnessMechanism", "Method"))

CIs = CIs %>% 
  mutate(beta_0_covered = ifelse((beta_0 >= est_beta_0 - 1.95 * emp_SE_beta_0) & (beta_0 <= est_beta_0 + 1.95 * emp_SE_beta_0), 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(beta_x_covered = ifelse((beta_x >= est_beta_1 - 1.95 * emp_SE_beta_x) & (beta_x <= est_beta_1 + 1.95 * emp_SE_beta_x), 1, 0))


CIs$Method = factor(
  CIs$Method,
  levels = c(
    "Calibrated Delta 1000",
    "Calibrated Delta 10000",
    "Calibrated Delta",
    "Standard MI",
    "CCA",
    "Full data"
  )
)

## 6 Levels: Calibrated Delta 1000 Calibrated Delta 10000 ... Full data
labs = c(expression(paste("Calibrated-", delta, ", ", n[ex], '= 1000')),
         expression(paste("Calibrated-", delta, ", ", n[ex], '= 10000')),
         expression(paste("Calibrated-", delta, ', fixed ', p[x]^{pop})),
         "Standard Multiple Imputation",
         "Complete Case Analysis",
         "Full Data")


Beta0CvgTbl = CIs %>%  
  group_by(MissingnessMechanism, Method) %>% 
  summarize(coverage_beta_0 = mean(beta_0_covered)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = MissingnessMechanism, values_from = coverage_beta_0) %>% 
  mutate(Method = factor(Method, levels = lvls)) %>% 
  arrange(Method)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'MissingnessMechanism' (override with `.groups` argument)
x = xtable(Beta0CvgTbl , digits = 3)
#print.xtable(x, type = "latex")

BetaxCvgTbl = CIs %>%  
  group_by(MissingnessMechanism, Method) %>% 
  summarize(coverage_beta_x = mean(beta_x_covered)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = MissingnessMechanism, values_from = coverage_beta_x) %>% 
  mutate(Method = factor(Method, levels = lvls)) %>% 
  arrange(Method)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'MissingnessMechanism' (override with `.groups` argument)
x = xtable(BetaxCvgTbl , digits = 3)
#print.xtable(x, type = "latex")

beta_0_coverage = CIs %>%
  group_by(MissingnessMechanism, Method) %>% 
  summarize(coverage_beta_0 = mean(beta_0_covered)) %>% 
  mutate(OutOfBounds =  coverage_beta_0 < 0.8,
         coverage_beta_0 = if_else(OutOfBounds, 0.8, coverage_beta_0)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = Method, x = coverage_beta_0, color = Method, shape = OutOfBounds)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  xlab(expression(paste("Coverage of ", beta[0]))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0.8, 1)) +
  labs(title = expression(paste("Coverage of ", beta[0]))) +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = labs) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(19, 4), guide = "none") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom", 
        legend.direction="vertical", 
        legend.text.align = 0,
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        strip.background =element_rect(fill="white")) +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  facet_wrap(~MissingnessMechanism, ncol = 1) 
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'MissingnessMechanism' (override with `.groups` argument)
beta_x_coverage = CIs %>%
  group_by(MissingnessMechanism, Method) %>% 
  summarize(coverage_beta_x = mean(beta_x_covered)) %>% 
  mutate(OutOfBounds =  coverage_beta_x < 0.8,
         coverage_beta_x = if_else(OutOfBounds, 0.8, coverage_beta_x)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = Method, x = coverage_beta_x, color = Method, shape = OutOfBounds)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  xlab(expression(paste("Coverage of ", beta[x]))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0.8, 1)) +
  labs(title = expression(paste("Coverage of ", beta[x]))) +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = labs) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(19, 4), guide = "none") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom", 
        legend.direction="vertical", 
        legend.text.align = 0,
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        strip.background =element_rect(fill="white")) +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  facet_wrap(~MissingnessMechanism, ncol = 1) 
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'MissingnessMechanism' (override with `.groups` argument)
# arrange the three plots in a single row
prow <- plot_grid(beta_0_coverage + theme(legend.position="none"),
           beta_x_coverage + theme(legend.position="none"),
           align = 'vh',
           #labels = c("A", "B", "C"),
           hjust = -1,
           nrow = 1
           )

# extract the legend from one of the plots
# (clearly the whole thing only makes sense if all plots
# have the same legend, so we can arbitrarily pick one.)
legend_b <- get_legend(beta_0_coverage + theme(legend.position="bottom"))

# add the legend underneath the row we made earlier. Give it 10% of the height
# of one plot (via rel_heights).
p <- plot_grid( prow, legend_b, ncol = 1, rel_heights = c(1, .2))
p
